Leptospirosis typically causes flu-like symptoms, including fever, chills, headache, body aches, [vomiting or nausea](https://www.foxnews.com/category/health/digestive-health), according to the CDC. Infected people may also experience yellowed eyes or skin, rash, stomach pain or diarrhea.

 ![Leptospirosis transmission](https://a57.foxnews.com/static.foxnews.com/foxnews.com/content/uploads/2026/01/1200/675/leptospira-transmission.jpg?ve=1&tl=1)

Rats and their urine are the primary vectors of the disease, officials warned. It can also be transmitted through contaminated soil or water exposed to infected animal urine. (iStock)

Without antibiotic treatment, the disease can lead to serious illness, including kidney damage, liver failure, meningitis and [difficulty breathing](https://www.foxnews.com/category/health/respiratory-health). In rare cases, it can be fatal to humans and animals, health officials say.

